Well, have you ever thought about why giraffes are speckled? This aesthetic appearance, in harmony with the grasslands, makes it hard for their enemies to distinguish the giraffes. Despite their giant bodies, they can thus hide from
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  the king of the savannah, that is the lion, their foremost enemy.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 In moments of danger, giraffes run at speeds of 55 to 60 kilometres (34 to 37 miles) per hour. When they begin to run, they move their heads back and forth like a pump, and curl their tails\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
. Unlike other animals, giraffes do not take crossed steps. That is, they move their left front and hind limbs first, and then the right front and hind limbs. Owing to this, lions are hardly able to catch giraffes.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 This is, no doubt, not the case for young\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 giraffes. With their premature and weak limbs, they cannot run as fast as their mothers. For this reason, they become easy prey for lions. Yet, as we mentioned earlier, these babies always remain with their mothers. With their long limbs, mothers can giv
