Elephants, the largest animals on land, have two major kinds of species; African and Asian elephants. African elephants are larger than the others. They may be as high as three and a half metres (12 feet) and their weight reach around six tons (12,000 po
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 unds). Their fan-shaped ears are two metres (6.5 feet) long and one and a half metres (5 feet) wide. As you can imagine, with such a giant body, you can't keep an elephant at home as a pet. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 What makes an elephant especially different is his trunk. This lo\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ng trunk, similar to a garden hose, includes fifty thousand muscles. What you have read is right: "50,000" muscles! Its nostrils are at the tip of this trunk. Elephants use their trunks to put food and water into their mouths, to lift things and, of cours
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , to smell. This trunk is capable of holding four litres of water. They either squirt this water into their mounts and drink it or spray it on their bodies. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Surprisingly, an elephant can even pick up a tiny pea seed with its trunk}{\f0\insrsid5189086 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  }{\f0\insrsid9850004\charrsid5189086 \loch\af0\dbch\af13\hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 which can lift such hu\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ge things \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 break it in its mouth and eat it. It is really amazing that such a huge animal can accomplish such delicate operations. This "multifunctional" trunk can be used as a long finger, a trumpet or sometimes as a loudspeaker. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  Besides that, elephant\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
s use their trunks to spray water on themselves to have a shower or throw dust on themselves for a dust-bath. Yet, new-born elephants fail to use their trunks. They sometimes even step on their trunks and fall down. We may find this amusing but surely the
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e little babies do not like it. A mother elephant accompanies her young elephant for twelve years. During the first six months, she teaches the baby how to use its trunk and she never becomes bored doing this. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 On both sides of their mouths, elephants have\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  two long sharp tusks. These tusks help them to protect themselves. Also, an elephant uses one of these tusks to dig holes in the ground and find water. 

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The teeth of these animals \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  which chew fibrous plants \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  wear out easily. For this reason, our Lord ha\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
s given them a very important characteristic: Every worn-out tooth is replaced by another in the back row. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 One full-grown elephant can eat 330 kilograms (726 pounds) of plants everyday. This amount is equal to six small bales of straw. Everyday, elephants\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  spend most of their time feeding themselves. 

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Now, let us give you another interesting piece of information about elephants. Have you ever thought how these huge thick-skinned animals cool themselves? As you might imagine, elephants cannot sweat because o
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
f their thick skins. Instead, they cool themselves with the help of the water and mud they see around. Of course, elephants have other methods to freshen themselves. For example, they use their ears as fans and cool their bodies with them. The thin blood 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 v\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 eins on their ears also cool them and cause overall refreshment. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Another feature of elephants has surprised hunters and zoologists for a long time. What astonished them was the rumbling of elephants' stomachs. While rumbling, elephants' stomachs make very\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 loud noises. Yet, what is astonishing is not the loudness of these noises but the way elephants control them. In fact these noises have nothing to do with digestion. The elephants make these noises to detect the location of their friends. More surprising
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 l\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
y, in the face of a danger, they all of a sudden become silent. Once they sense the threat is over, they start making noise again. Thanks to this method, elephants can communicate with one another even from four kilometres away. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Th\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e migration stories of elephants have always astonished zoologists. These animals with their giant ears and huge bodies migrate in the dry seasons and always follow the same paths. What is even more interesting is that they clean up garbage such as chips 
